Will The New Products Help GoPro Stock? - GoPro Inc (NASDAQ:GPRO)











































Home > Stocks Market News - Articles & Analysis > Stock Market News > Will The New Products Help GoPro Stock? - GoPro Inc (NASDAQ:GPRO) 














		Will The New Products Help GoPro Stock? - GoPro Inc (NASDAQ:GPRO)		


 




 







 


 



Posted by Kumar Abhishek
on May 24, 2017, 07:08 AM EST

Related Ticker: GPRO 


 
GoPro Inc (NASDAQ:GPRO) stock is facing strong resistance from the 100-day moving average line.

Flickr
After reporting better than expected revenue growth in Q1, action camera maker GoPro Inc (NASDAQ:GPRO) is on track to achieve its Q2 targets, according to CEO Nick Woodman. GoPro is in the middle of a turnaround process which has not borne the desired results till now, though there has been some progress. The company has taken several steps including restructuring and product diversification. However, the company is not out of the woods yet. GoPro's Hero line of cameras still command strong customer loyalty. Hero cameras are one of the best in their class. According to The NPD Group's Retail Tracking Service, Hero camera's occupied top three spots in the digital image category in the United States. But that has not helped the company or the stock much in the past two years. GPRO stock is down 84% in the last two years and almost flat YTD.    



What is holding down GoPro Inc?
There are several reasons for GoPro's struggles. While GoPro's cameras are of high quality, it serves a very niche market. There are now indications that the niche action camera market may be saturating. And improving camera quality in mobile phones such as the iPhone and Galaxy Note will make wider adoption of GoPro's Hero line of cameras difficult. Apart from the niche market, GoPro is also facing strong competition from much cheaper action cameras. While the competitors may not be able to match GoPro's quality, they provide the same functionality at a much cheaper price.  


  
Then there is also the execution problem. Last holiday season, GoPro managed to botch the release of its much-awaited Hero 5 line of Cameras as well as the Karma drone. Manufacturing issues led to delay in the delivery of Hero 5 Black camera during the all-important holiday season. More importantly, GoPro was forced to recall its much-hyped Karma drones due to technical issues. The recall was announced after GoPro discovered that Karma drones were prone to crashing mid-flight due to a sudden loss of power. The recall did a great damage to GoPro's brand name. And this was not the first big launch which GoPro had flubbed. Even Hero 4 launch didn't go as planned. GoPro was forced to slash its price within few months of the launch and take a hit of millions of dollars in inventory write-downs.  
Product diversification.
While action cameras remain GoPro's main revenue source, the company has been diversifying into other product markets. Apart from the Karma drone, GoPro has also launched subscription service for photo and video editing and sharing. Diversification will help to increase GoPro's total addressable market and reduce the business risk. However, both Karma and the subscription service didn't have a perfect start. The recall of Karma during the all-important holiday season was a big blow to the brand and the timing didn't help either. Given the negative brand image and strong competition from Chinese drone manufacturer DJI, GoPro will have to invest significant time and money in the drone to make it appeal to customers once again. Karma drone lacked several features such as "collision avoidance" and "follow me", which are now staple features in most of the drones.    



Further, the action camera company announced the pilot launch of Fusion 5.2K spherical camera. Fusion is a 360-degree spherical camera that's supposed to allow you to reframe images in 2D shots and see full-field of view in VR. VR is a rapidly growing market which could be a big opportunity for GoPro. According to statista.com, VR hardware market is expected to grow from $3.2 billion in 2016 to $15.9 billion in 2020. While Karma was diversification into an industry in which GoPro didn't have much experience, Fusion is a perfect example of product extension in GoPro's core business in which the company has considerable expertise.  


  
GoPro stock remains a risky bet.
GoPro's recent launches have failed to live up to their promise till now. With the growth in action camera market slowing down, GoPro needs another product to drive its growth. The company's decision to enter the VR market through Fusion camera is a good move, though it might be some time before it has any impact on GoPro's top line. Given the challenges, GoPro stock remains a risky long-term bet.    
Check out our daily stocks to buy for daily trading ideas. Looking for great tech stocks? Check out Amigobulls' top stocks to buy, which have beaten the NASDAQ by around 130%. We also have our set of top picks from the auto sector, which have beaten the S&P 500 by over 180%.








